the mad women project disability and the aesthetics of human disqualification events at stanford the mad women project disability and the aesthetics of human disqualification facebook twitter email print add to calendar a presentation by tobin siebers department of english language and literature art & design university of michigan which takes its departure from a series of photographs by park young sook called the mad women project with the goal of debating significant arguments designed by the field of disability studies from 1999 to 2005 park investigated the representation of women with mental disabilities by photographing gestures and postures uded to identify women as crazy prof tobins examines the physical echoes of cognitive and intellectual disability interrogating how aesthetics particitates in the disqualification of disabled people as inferior and considers the mad women project in the context of feminist theory and the work of cindy sherman when thursday october 27 2011 4 15 pm approximate duration of 1.5 hour s where terrace room margaret jacks hall bldg 460 fourth floor map audience faculty staff alumni friends general public students members tags humanities public service other visual health wellness arts sponsor comparative literature program in modern thought and literature department of english contact 650 725 1477 monica moore stanford edu admission free and open to the public permalink http events stanford edu events 295 29541 last modified october 20 2011
